Bitcoin (BTC): The world's first decentralized currency¶

  • 18 August 2008, the domain name bitcoin.org was registered
  • 31 October 2008, a link to a paper authored by Satoshi Nakamoto titled Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System was posted to a cryptography mailing list
  • 3 January 2009, the bitcoin network came into existence with Satoshi Nakamoto mining the genesis block of bitcoin (block number 0), which had a reward of 50 bitcoins

Key Features¶

  • Governance: Decentralized

  • Balances: Blockchain

  • Transactions: Private Keys

  • Processing: Mining

Importance and Issues¶

  • Bitcoin (BTC) is the largest cryptocurrency in existence today with a market capitalization of $174.5bn as of February 19, 2020

  • For perspective, Bitcoin market value is larger than 468 of the companies that comprise the S&P 500 index

  • The blockchain is immutable, all transactions are verified and published publicly

  • The volatility of Bitcoin’s price has been a major issue

  • The vast majority of the industry and investors focus on technical analysis and misinformation

Current Trends¶

Cryptocurrency Market¶

  • The Bitcoin halving in May 2020
  • 633,021 wallets (2.7%) hold 1,675,770 BTC (95.4%)

Key Question¶

Is the value of the network the driving factor behind Bitcoin's price?¶

  • Can we identify changes in the network value using on-chain metrics and translate these into a signal that identifies the directional trend of Bitcoin prices for use in an algorithmic trading strategy

  • After all, over $1.0bn is traded daily between investors thus making for an extremely compelling use case

Proposed Product¶

Signal¶

  • A weekly trend signal using on-chain metrics that provides a Long or Short Direction prediction for the upcoming week

Value¶

  • A signal with high accuracy and recall is very valuable to end users including investors, traders, miners, service providers, and researchers involved with the blockchain industry

Implementation¶

Data collection¶

  • Data validation performed comparing Quandl, Glassnode, CoinGecko, Blockchain and CryptoCompare API data prior to selecting Quandl and Glassnode
  • Data consists of historical daily price data from 2014-04-15 to the present day
  • On-chain metrics historical data ranges vary with minimum of 8 years of daily data
  • 30 API endpoints

Data Exploration¶

  • Active Addresses, Unrealized Profit & Loss, Velocity, UTXO, Active Supply, Exchange Flows, MVRV Ratio, Spent Output Profit Ratio, BTC Circulation and Miner Hashrate

Feature Engineering¶

  • Daily data was resampled into weeky data and converted to percentage change
  • Features include Stock-to-Flow, Active Addresses-to-Active Entities and Moving Averages
  • Top Features are the Weekly Change in Unrealized Profit & Loss and MVRV Ratio

Modeling¶

Supervised Learning¶

  • Classic Models
  • Ensemble Models
  • Neural Networks

Unsupervised Learning¶

  • K-Means for clustering

Methodology Notes: Model Process, Tuning and Selection¶

  • After creating a classification problem I used K-means to see if there are any discernible features based on clustering of the two classes and found little useful information
  • Feature Importance was used to decrease the dimensionality from 65 to 11 features
  • Applied Classic supervised learning models due to speed and applied these as the baseline
  • Utilized TPOT for AutoML with no improvement in the results
  • Applied Ensemble algorithms with the goal of improving the accuracy, fit and generalization through model selection
  • All models were tuned using GridSearchCV with a 3 cross folds
  • TimeSeriesSplit Cross Validaition was performed as the data is sequential making shuffling inappropriate
  • Mutliple Neural Networks was constructed in order to find a model that performed better than both Classic and Ensemble models
  • Neural Networks were optimized through numerous combinations over a series of days as well as the use of Talos
  • The final model was a customized LSTM that incorporated a timestep in the input layer resulting in a significant increase in the models accuracy and a reduction in the loss rate
  • The key optimization of the selected model included adjusting the timestep and regularization through adjustment of the the dropout rate, neurons, batch_size and epochs through multiple combinations

Model Deployment¶

  • The TS-LSTM is the best performing model
  • The model and scaler were saved for use in code that automatically pulls new weekly data and provides a forward prediction

Automated Order Execution System¶

XBT Chart by TradingView
  • The signal is integrated into the indicator module of the automated order execution system that enters 3 to 4 long or short orders based on the signals output
  • Orders are placed hourly based on a computation for liquidation levels of leveraged positions

Results and Summary¶

  • Performance since the signal was created using RFC & TS-LSTM from January 8th to February 16th is +32.7% v BTC +21.8% in the live account and from February 17th to February 20th using the fully automated TS-LSTM is +5.0% v BTC -3.2% in the test account

  • The pricing of the APIs from the service providers currently ranges from Glassnode USD39 (Limited access and delayed) to USD599 for full access to TokenAnalyst at USD799 per month and ITB at Price on Request

  • Data as costly as these services validates professional and enterprise demand for these services

Future Work¶

  • Scale the live trading account to 1.0 BTC
  • Experiment with more complex Neural Networks using in reinforcement learning
  • Extract the average leverage of BTC Perpetual Swaps using K-Means for clustering of the exchange orderbook data
